<div id="node-269" class="node node-type-story node-promoted node-teaser build-mode-teaser"><div class="node-inner">

  
      <h2 class="title">
      <a href="/node/269" title="Article:  Why Spring JDBC?">Article:  Why Spring JDBC?</a>
    </h2>
  
  
      <div class="meta">
              <div class="submitted">
          Submitted by Thomas Risberg on Thu, 2006-05-11 11:27        </div>
      
              <div class="terms terms-inline"> in <ul class="links inline"><li class="taxonomy_term_6 first last active"><a href="/presentations" rel="tag" title="A link to a technical article about Spring" class="active">Technical Article</a></li>
</ul></div>
          </div>
  
  <div class="content">
    <p>Vikram Veeravelu has written an <a href="http://today.java.net/pub/a/today/2006/05/09/why-spring-jdbc.html" target="_self">article</a> discussing the use of Spring JDBC over direct use of the JDBC API.&nbsp; It's published on java.net and is a good introduction for anyone interested in trying the Spring JDBC library.</p>
  </div>

  <ul class="links inline"><li class="comment_comments first last"><a href="/node/269#comments" title="Jump to the first comment of this posting.">42 comments</a></li>
</ul>
</div></div> <!-- /node-inner, /node -->
<div id="node-255" class="node node-type-story node-promoted node-teaser build-mode-teaser"><div class="node-inner">

  
      <h2 class="title">
      <a href="/node/255" title="Article: LdapTemplate: LDAP Programming in Java Made Simple">Article: LdapTemplate: LDAP Programming in Java Made Simple</a>
    </h2>
  
  
      <div class="meta">
              <div class="submitted">
          Submitted by Colin Sampaleanu on Wed, 2006-04-19 09:19        </div>
      
              <div class="terms terms-inline"> in <ul class="links inline"><li class="taxonomy_term_6 first last active"><a href="/presentations" rel="tag" title="A link to a technical article about Spring" class="active">Technical Article</a></li>
</ul></div>
          </div>
  
  <div class="content">
    <p>In <em><a target="_self" href="http://today.java.net/pub/a/today/2006/04/18/ldaptemplate-java-ldap-made-simple.html">LdapTemplate: LDAP Programming in Java Made Simple</a></em>, Mattias Arthursson and Ulrik Sandberg write about the LdapTemplate library, which brings JdbcTemplate-like functionality to the world of LDAP.</p><p>Note that we expect that LdapTemplate will make its way into Spring itself in the near term.&nbsp;</p>  </div>

  <ul class="links inline"><li class="comment_comments first last"><a href="/node/255#comments" title="Jump to the first comment of this posting.">13 comments</a></li>
</ul>
</div></div> <!-- /node-inner, /node -->
<div id="node-249" class="node node-type-story node-promoted node-teaser build-mode-teaser"><div class="node-inner">

  
      <h2 class="title">
      <a href="/node/249" title="Article: Develop Spring applications for IBM WebSphere Application Server -- Part 1">Article: Develop Spring applications for IBM WebSphere Application Server -- Part 1</a>
    </h2>
  
  
      <div class="meta">
              <div class="submitted">
          Submitted by Colin Sampaleanu on Sat, 2006-04-01 13:32        </div>
      
              <div class="terms terms-inline"> in <ul class="links inline"><li class="taxonomy_term_6 first last active"><a href="/presentations" rel="tag" title="A link to a technical article about Spring" class="active">Technical Article</a></li>
</ul></div>
          </div>
  
  <div class="content">
    <p><a href="http://www-128.ibm.com/developerworks/websphere/techjournal/0603_patil/0603_patil1.html" target="_self">Develop Spring applications for IBM WebSphere Application Server -- Part 1</a>, by Sunil Patil, is the first article of a three-part series from IBM developerWorks , which  walks through developing a J2EE application for the WebSphere app server using Spring Framework and IBM's Rational Application Developer. This first article mostly focuses on Spring concepts such as the bean factory, AOP, and how to integrate Spring and Struts applications.</p>
  </div>

